07/10 14:23:35 - OpenCompass - INFO - ChatCompletion(id='chatcmpl-b787f083e0439c7a', choices=[Choice(finish_reason='stop', index=0, logprobs=None, message=ChatCompletionMessage(content='**Summary: The Role and Responsibilities of the House Minority Leader**\n\nThis report outlines the function, history, and strategic challenges of the House Minority Leader, the head of the "loyal opposition" in the U.S. House of Representatives. The position\'s primary objective is to recapture majority control of the House, a goal that defines the leader\'s activities despite the institutional reality of majority rule. Traditionally, the Minority Leader is an experienced lawmaker elected by secret ballot every two years, serving as the party\'s chief spokesperson and strategist.\n\nHistorically, the role is a late-19th-century innovation. Prior to this era, congressional parties were often disorganized, lacking formal leadership titles. While figures like James Madison informally led opposition in the early Republic, the official position of Minority Leader solidified by 1883, coinciding with the rise of strong partisan attachments and organized party structures. Originally, the leader also served as the ranking member on powerful committees like Rules and Ways and Means, though today the role focuses on party leadership and institutional prerogatives.\n\nThe Minority Leader\'s duties are twofold: managing party responsibilities and fulfilling institutional obligations. As a party leader, the official acts as a campaigner, raising funds, recruiting candidates, and coordinating with national committees to win elections. Strategically, the leader must navigate various approaches to legislation, ranging from cooperation and innovation to partisan opposition and obstruction. These tactics are employed to highlight majority failures, protect party interests, and present a unified, electorally attractive agenda. When the President is of the same party, the leader often acts as a "point man" to advance the administration\'s goals; conversely, when the President is of the opposing party, the leader serves as a national spokesperson offering policy alternatives. Internally, the leader must foster unity through constant consultation, task forces, and inclusive decision-making to manage a diverse caucus.\n\nInstitutionally, the Minority Leader holds specific powers granted by House rules to ensure minority rights are protected. These include the right to offer a motion to recommit with instructions, priority for questions of privilege, and a role in appointing the Inspector General and members of the Ethics Committee. The leader also serves as an ex officio member of the Intelligence Committee and participates in various commissions. Despite these formal powers, the leader faces the central dilemma of "inferior numbers," which limits their ability to set the legislative agenda. Ultimately, the Minority Leader must balance the need to criticize the majority constructively with the necessity of building a coalition to regain power, navigating a complex political landscape where electoral success depends on factors often beyond their direct control.', refusal=None, role='assistant', annotations=None, audio=None, function_call=None, tool_calls=[], reasoning=None), stop_reason=None, token_ids=None)], created=1783664585, model='Qwen3.5-27B', object='chat.completion', service_tier=None, system_fingerprint=None, usage=CompletionUsage(completion_tokens=535, prompt_tokens=5842, total_tokens=6377, completion_tokens_details=None, prompt_tokens_details=None), prompt_logprobs=None, prompt_token_ids=None, kv_transfer_params=None)

