acks. Following the 2009 shootings at Fort Hood, Texas, and Little Rock, Arkansas, Congress passed the National Defense Authorization Act (NDAA) for Fiscal Year 2015. This legislation redefined eligibility to include attacks by individuals "inspired or motivated" by foreign terrorist organizations, even if the perpetrator was not a formal member of such a group. This change allowed victims of the Fort Hood and Little Rock shootings, as well as the 2015 Chattanooga recruiting center attack, to receive the Purple Heart. This expansion has sparked debate over whether the award should apply to domestic criminal acts or only traditional battlefield injuries, with critics fearing it may dilute the medal\'s meaning.\n\nAdditionally, the report notes legislative efforts to protect the integrity of the award, such as the "Private Corrado Piccoli Purple Heart Preservation Act," which seeks to criminalize the sale of Purple Hearts. It also details recent expansions of benefits for recipients, including commissary and morale, welfare, and recreation (MWR) privileges for veterans and their caregivers. As the military continues to face evolving threats and new types of injuries, the report concludes that Congress and the executive branch will likely continue to grapple with balancing the need to honor all forms of service-related sacrifice against the desire to maintain the Purple Heart\'s historical significance as a symbol of valor in direct combat.', refusal=None, role='assistant', annotations=None, audio=None, function_call=None, tool_calls=[], reasoning=None), stop_reason=None, token_ids=None)], created=1783664740, model='Qwen3.5-27B', object='chat.completion', service_tier=None, system_fingerprint=None, usage=CompletionUsage(completion_tokens=600, prompt_tokens=6571, total_tokens=7171, completion_tokens_details=None, prompt_tokens_details=None), prompt_logprobs=None, prompt_token_ids=None, kv_transfer_params=None)

