solvent standard at the end of 2017, and the U.S. Virgin Islands held a significant outstanding federal loan. The Extended Benefit (EB) program, which can extend benefits by 13 to 20 weeks during high unemployment, was not active in any state at the time of publication. The Department of Labor (DOL) continues to administer the Reemployment Services and Eligibility Assessment (RESEA) program to assist claimants in finding work and preventing fraud.\n\nLooking forward, the President\'s FY2020 budget proposal suggests significant reforms, including a new solvency standard for state accounts, a mandatory paid parental leave benefit financed through UI taxes, and stricter integrity measures such as mandatory data cross-checks and offsets for Social Security Disability Insurance recipients. Additionally, the report details ongoing legislative efforts to expand eligibility, including the Violence Against Women Reauthorization Act (allowing benefits for those quitting due to harassment or abuse) and the ELEVATE Act (proposing self-employment and relocation assistance). Finally, the DOL is navigating complex legal challenges regarding drug testing rules for UI applicants following a Congressional Review Act repeal of a 2016 regulation, with a new, more flexible rule proposed in 2018.', refusal=None, role='assistant', annotations=None, audio=None, function_call=None, tool_calls=[], reasoning=None), stop_reason=None, token_ids=None)], created=1783664826, model='Qwen3.5-27B', object='chat.completion', service_tier=None, system_fingerprint=None, usage=CompletionUsage(completion_tokens=626, prompt_tokens=4931, total_tokens=5557, completion_tokens_details=None, prompt_tokens_details=None), prompt_logprobs=None, prompt_token_ids=None, kv_transfer_params=None)

