training and guidance varied widely. DOD and the Department of Homeland Security (DHS) have implemented updated, specific training and detailed guidance to assist contracting officers. In contrast, the Department of Veterans Affairs (VA) and the Department of Health and Human Services (HHS) lacked comprehensive agency-level training or specific guidance, leading to confusion among staff regarding threshold calculations, waiver applicability, and documentation requirements. The GAO found instances where agencies incorrectly applied trade agreement waivers to contracts below the required dollar thresholds or failed to obtain necessary approvals for domestic non-availability exceptions.\n\nTo address these deficiencies, the GAO issued four recommendations. The Office of Management and Budget (OMB) is urged to facilitate improved training and clarify FPDS-NG reporting requirements to enhance data accuracy. The Secretaries of DHS, VA, and HHS are recommended to provide clearer guidance and training to help contracting officials determine the applicability of trade agreements, properly document exceptions, and verify product origin information. While agencies generally agreed with the findings, the GAO noted that VA\'s response did not fully address the need for specific guidance on trade agreement waivers and product verification. Ensuring accurate data and consistent implementation is critical for congressional oversight and maintaining the integrity of domestic purchasing preferences.', refusal=None, role='assistant', annotations=None, audio=None, function_call=None, tool_calls=[], reasoning=None), stop_reason=None, token_ids=None)], created=1783664910, model='Qwen3.5-27B', object='chat.completion', service_tier=None, system_fingerprint=None, usage=CompletionUsage(completion_tokens=584, prompt_tokens=11840, total_tokens=12424, completion_tokens_details=None, prompt_tokens_details=None), prompt_logprobs=None, prompt_token_ids=None, kv_transfer_params=None)
