07/10 14:32:07 - OpenCompass - INFO - ChatCompletion(id='chatcmpl-98923c89e1605fbf', choices=[Choice(finish_reason='stop', index=0, logprobs=None, message=ChatCompletionMessage(content='**Summary of Congressional Compensation Report**\n\nThis report details the constitutional framework, historical evolution, and legislative mechanisms governing the compensation of Members of the U.S. Congress. Grounded in Article I, Section 6, and the Twenty-Seventh Amendment, the latter of which mandates that any salary changes cannot take effect until after an intervening election, the document outlines how Member pay is ascertained and funded. Since Fiscal Year 1983, salaries have been drawn from a permanent appropriations account. As of the most recent adjustment in January 2009, the standard salary for Senators, Representatives, Delegates, and the Resident Commissioner of Puerto Rico is $174,000. Leadership positions command higher rates: the Speaker of the House earns $223,500, while the President pro tempore of the Senate and the majority and minority leaders in both chambers earn $193,400.\n\nThe report identifies three primary methods for adjusting Member pay. Prior to 1968, adjustments required specific legislation. From 1967 to 1989, a quadrennial commission recommended increases for top federal officials, a process utilized three times. The current system, established by the Ethics Reform Act of 1989, utilizes an automatic annual adjustment formula based on the Employment Cost Index (ECI) for private sector wages. Under this system, adjustments take effect automatically unless Congress statutorily prohibits them, revises them, or if the General Schedule (GS) federal employee base pay increase is lower, in which case Member pay is capped at the GS rate.\n\nA significant portion of the report analyzes the frequent statutory prohibitions of these automatic adjustments. Since the implementation of the ECI formula, Congress has denied or frozen pay adjustments in 16 of the years between 1994 and 2019. These prohibitions are typically enacted through provisions in annual appropriations bills or continuing resolutions, often without separate votes. Consequently, while the ECI formula projected various increases over the years, the actual salary has remained frozen at the 2009 level for over a decade. The report notes that had Members received every projected adjustment since 1992, the 2019 salary would have been approximately $210,900; instead, inflation-adjusted salaries have decreased by 15% since 2009.\n\nFurthermore, the document catalogs extensive legislative efforts from the 112th through the 116th Congresses aimed at altering the compensation structure. These proposals include repealing the automatic adjustment provision entirely, linking pay to specific congressional actions (such as passing a budget resolution or avoiding a government shutdown), reducing salaries, or freezing pay during debt limit crises. While some measures, such as holding salaries in escrow if a budget is not passed by a certain date, were enacted, they were often rendered moot by subsequent congressional actions. The report concludes by providing historical tables and data visualizations illustrating the divergence between projected and actual pay, highlighting the long-term trend of salary stagnation relative to inflation.', refusal=None, role='assistant', annotations=None, audio=None, function_call=None, tool_calls=[], reasoning=None), stop_reason=None, token_ids=None)], created=1783665075, model='Qwen3.5-27B', object='chat.completion', service_tier=None, system_fingerprint=None, usage=CompletionUsage(completion_tokens=641, prompt_tokens=8601, total_tokens=9242, completion_tokens_details=None, prompt_tokens_details=None), prompt_logprobs=None, prompt_token_ids=None, kv_transfer_params=None)

